Hello David,

Thanks for meeting with us again. We confirmed what you were seeing and provided in your screen shots before:
No jobs are running, but the FileSystem job's task stats show several server scans are still running and have no duration.

We checked the Job groups folder and found a "running.lck" file was still present. This "lock" file should only be there while the job is running. It seems like either the previous scan didn't end properly or two jobs were trying scan the same resource at once. Either way, we deleted the running.lck file and kick off the scan again.

Please let me know how it goes.

Thank you,

Joshua Sexton

Hello David,

I'm not sure why the custom attributes are still failing. Looking through my notes, I don't think we captured the error with custom attributes. If it's still available, could you send me a screenshot or copy/paste that error?


Yes, you can remove them and add them back later. The custom attributes configuration is a bit buried, but here's where to find it:

NEA > Expand Jobs group > Expand .Active Directory Inventory group > Expand 1-AD_Scan Job > Expand Configure node > Right-click Queries > Select Properties

Query Properties Pop-up > Click Configure

Active Directory Inventory DC Wizard Pop-up > Select the Custom Attributes tab

[cid:image008.png@01DB31BE.756F3050]
[cid:image009.png@01DB31BE.756F3050]


Please let me know if that helps. Looking through my notes, I don't we captured the error with custom attributes. If it's still available, could you send me a screenshot of that error?

Hello David,

Unfortunately, there are several steps needed to switch Netwrix Activity Monitor and Netwrix Enterprise Auditor over to auditing the new server even though the name is the same. We should create a new ticket for performing this change.

Do you know when they are migrating the data over?

You will need to remove the agent from the old server in Netwrix Activity Monitor and re-add agent to that server to ush the agent out to the new server. You will then need to re-configure the Monitored Host Output to make sure it's collecting the data you want from the new server and still sending it to Netwrix Enterprise Auditor.

The Netwrix Enterprise Auditor side gets a little trickier. Assuming you want to keep the data from your old server, you'll need to add the new server to the host list as a new host with a different name (FQDN if you had used CommonName or CommonName if you had used FQDN).

You'll also need to change that server's output file in Netwrix Activity Monitor to report as whatever you name the server in NEA.

This sounds more complicated than it is, but I'd still like to help wit this over a remote session. Please let me know when they are making that change, and I'll open a new ticket for this.

Thank you,

Joshua Sexton
Technical Support Engineer Tier 1

Hello David,

Unfortunately, there are several steps needed to switch Netwrix Activity Monitor and Netwrix Enterprise Auditor over to auditing the new server even though the name is the same. We should create a new ticket for performing this change.

Do you know when they are migrating the data over?

You will need to remove the agent from the old server in Netwrix Activity Monitor and re-add agent to that server to ush the agent out to the new server. You will then need to re-configure the Monitored Host Output to make sure it's collecting the data you want from the new server and still sending it to Netwrix Enterprise Auditor.

The Netwrix Enterprise Auditor side gets a little trickier. Assuming you want to keep the data from your old server, you'll need to add the new server to the host list as a new host with a different name (FQDN if you had used CommonName or CommonName if you had used FQDN). 

You'll also need to change that server's output file in Netwrix Activity Monitor to report as whatever you name the server in NEA.

This sounds more complicated than it is, but I'd still like to help wit this over a remote session. Please let me know when they are making that change, and I'll open a new ticket for this.

Thank you,
